The movement was driven by the context of the June 2013 Days, when millions of people took to the streets of Brazil demanding improvements in public transport, education and health, as well as protesting against corruption and the excessive spending on the 2014 World Cup.

On July 11, 2013, workers from various categories (metalworkers, bank workers, teachers, dockworkers, bus drivers, etc.), with the support of the country's main trade union centrals (CUT, Força Sindical, CTB, UGT, among others), held stoppages, road blockades and demonstrations in various capitals and cities in the countryside.

**Main demands of the July 11 Movement: **
- Reduction of the working day to 40 hours a week with no reduction in pay;
- An end to the social security factor;
- Better wages and working conditions;
- Investment in health, education and public transport;
- Land reform;
- Against the privatization of ports, airports and highways.

The movement was marked by peaceful actions, but also saw some clashes between demonstrators and police forces, as well as blockades of important avenues and highways in the country.

**Historical importance
The 11 July Movement demonstrated the strength of the Brazilian workers' mobilization and marked a moment of unity between different trade union federations, which traditionally had differences. It also broadened the agenda of the 2013 demonstrations, putting workers' demands even more strongly on the public agenda.

If you want to know more about any specific aspect of the movement, feel free to ask!

